                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d939">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">852.48/771</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Secretary of State</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-10-07">October 7,
                            1940</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The British Ambassador,<note n="29" xml:id="d939fn29">Lord Lothian.</note>
                    accompanied by Mr. N. M. Butler, Counselor of the British Embassy, called at his
                    request. The Ambassador spoke about our proposal to supply some foodstuffs to
                    Spain under given conditions. He said that his Government was in harmony with
                    this view and that this was the psychological time for such action. He seemed to
                    have in mind olive oil as one commodity that might be considered as part payment
                    for any loan we might make for foodstuffs, adding that this would be in addition
                    to cork and quicksilver.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>C[<hi rend="smallcaps">ordell</hi>] H[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                        >ull</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
